ğŸ› ï¸ To properly rename the hostname on an Ubuntu EC2 instance:
Use hostnamectl to change the hostname:

sudo hostnamectl set-hostname new-hostname
Update /etc/hosts (optional but recommended for local name resolution):

sudo nano /etc/hosts
Update the line:

127.0.1.1    old-hostname
to:

127.0.1.1    new-hostname
Verify:

hostname
hostnamectl
Reboot (optional but ensures everything reflects the new name):

sudo reboot
ğŸ” After a stop/start?
As long as you're not using cloud-init to reapply a default hostname, and nothing resets it via automation (e.g., a user-data script), the new hostname stays.

ğŸ§  Bonus Tip: Prevent hostname reset by cloud-init (just in case)
If youâ€™re using cloud-init, sometimes it resets the hostname on boot. You can prevent this by:

Edit:

sudo nano /etc/cloud/cloud.cfg
Find this line:

preserve_hostname: false
Change it to:

preserve_hostname: true
Then:

sudo hostnamectl set-hostname your-hostname
